<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Dempster Highway (and ITH to Tuktoyaktuk)</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Dempster Highway (and ITH to Tuktoyaktuk)</h2><p><i>Yukon / NWT, Canada · YT-5 / NT-8, Dawson City to Tuktoyaktuk</i></p><p><b>Gravel road to the Arctic Ocean — 736 km on the Dempster, +147 km on the all-season ITH.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>719 km (447 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 days each way</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late June–mid September (river ferries operating); ice-road season in Feb/Mar</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Gravel devastates windshields and tires; no fuel for 369 km between Dawson and Eagle Plains; bears; weather; spring breakup makes ferries impossible</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>1015</td></tr></table><hr><p>One of only two roads to the Arctic Ocean in North America (the other is the Dalton in Alaska). Gravel/dirt for nearly the entire length — muddy when wet, dust-clouded when dry. Carry two spare tires, full fuel, and patience for windshield cracks. The road is named for Inspector Dempster of the RNWMP, who in 1911 was sent to find the Lost Patrol — Mounties who'd died trying to make the same trip on dogsled. Late August is the magic season: fall colors flame across the tundra, mosquitoes are gone, the rivers still ferry. The Inuvik–Tuktoyaktuk Highway opened in 2017, finally giving Canada an all-season road to the Arctic Ocean.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Tombstone Territorial Park</b> — Jagged black peaks ('the Patagonia of the North'), with an interpretive center and a campground. Late-August colors are world-class.</li><li><b>Engineer Creek</b> — Sulfurous springs stain the streambed bright orange. Iron-rich rock; smells like a struck match. Rough campground.</li><li><b>Eagle Plains Hotel</b> — Only services for hundreds of km in either direction. Fuel, beds, food, mechanic. Built directly on permafrost — the building leans gently with the seasons.</li><li><b>Arctic Circle marker</b> — Stand on 66°33′N. Sign and small parking pullout. Photo-op. North of here, the sun does not set on June 21st.</li><li><b>Peel River ferry</b> — Free year-round crossing — boat in summer, ice road in winter. During spring breakup and fall freeze-up the road is impassable.</li><li><b>Igloo Church (Inuvik)</b> — Our Lady of Victory — 1960 wooden Catholic church built in the shape of an igloo, painted blue and white. Open to visitors.</li><li><b>Tuktoyaktuk pingos</b> — Ice-cored hills — Tuk has the densest concentration on Earth (1,350 of them). Ibyuk, the largest, is 49 m tall and visible from town.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
